        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>July 28/77</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>It would be a great pleasure to me to give you any information, but I dare not trust my memory after so long an interval. In my little paper I have given only facts which were recorded at the time.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> My impression however is that “mum” arose from opening &amp; shutting the mouth repeatedly as a sign of wanting to eat, for this movement makes a sound like the letter m. I feel sure that several of the consonants (m, b &amp; d being excepted) were much more difficult for my children to utter correctly than the vowels. I can only repeat my regret that I cannot aid you in your very interesting investigation.</p>
<p>I remain, dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Sayce had asked CD to expand on comments he made in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8641.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Biographical sketch of an infant’</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11074.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from A. H. Sayce, 27 July 1877</ref>).</note>
